history.content: There are a few classes that overlap (189, 182, 106a, etc). However, there are quite a few grad classes that do not overlap. Also different grad classes are offered each semester (usually labeled as 294). More information could be found at guide.berkeley.edu or in the draft schedule: https://www2.eecs.berkeley.edu/Scheduling/CS/schedule-draft.html.

children.subject: No, that is not true for all courses. Course listings like 189 and 289A are the same course and therefore you would not take both. However, classes like 161 and 261 are actually different and 261 covers topics that are not covered in 161. The same thing is true for 162, 262a, and 262b. All 3 of these courses cover different material. You should look into the specific class to see whether it is just the undergrad course under a different listing.

Thanks, and as a follow up is it safe to assume the classes that are the same number but 200 instead of 100 are essentially the same? For ex. 161 and 261 which both are about security. I heard there is no point in taking the grad version if you took the undergrad

history.content: I have a question regarding graduate classes for eecs/cs at cal, a lot of the classes are the same as the upper divs for undergrads. So, isn't the program repetitive? I want to be learning new things, and there are a couple of new classes, but majority are the same.
